i don't know why i am avoiding my eyes in the mirror. i don't know why i fail to see what everyone sees. i don't hate myself. i'm still sane enough to know what things will push me over the edge. but still, whenever i try to tell myself a few words, i can't help but feel i am talking to a stranger. my mother is always annoyed whenever i deny a photo. she asks me why and i tell her i don't feel like it. but we both know that's not the case, we both know there's something else. and she keeps asking me, nevertheless. maybe hoping that i will change my mind. .
.
.

.

.

nov 10 christian belton and i head to do the work of the lord.  i have spent an entire year planning and coordinating.  i heard a voice say launch this inaugural project in nigeria and i obeyed.  i have no corporate sponsors yet for this project but a few wonderful people have sowed into the vision.  however, the expenses far outweigh the donations but i trust god.  this project is about helping those who have been violated and hurt in such a way thatâ€™s unimaginable.  many survivors have never received counseling services.  many survivors feel they wonâ€™t be believed or heard so they stay quiet.  i care so much for each survivor.  i have been sent across the ocean to help.  i have been sent to say there is hope.  god has gifted me to teach. so me and a few others will train attendees on what best practices help women become restored. 
i am uber excited about the 8 interns coming from the university of abuja to volunteer as stars volunteer ambassadors.  each have been given a volunteer assignment and will also sit and be trained at the project.  i need to pay for their transportation to the training as we know many students donâ€™t have lots of money. 
there are things that still need to be covered.  i am flying in a few young girls from a recovery house with the program director.  these young girls have been illicitly touched before.  that pains me.  we will encourage and celebrate them at the opening night gala. 
i need financial help getting them to abuja and back to lagos. 
sow a seed for a wonderful cause.  thank you in advance.  thank you to all who sowed already.

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
a root of bitterness

hebrews 12:12-15

if youâ€™ve ever tried to get rid of weeds in your lawn or garden, you know what a big problem they can be. you pull them out, and everything looks really good for a while, but before long, the unwanted growth returns because the roots are still there.
an unforgiving spirit is like a root branching out in all directions, affecting every area of our life. lopping off the leaves by repressing the pain and resentment isnâ€™t a long-term solution, because like a weed, bitterness can continue to grow and reproduce as long as roots are in place.

when weâ€™ve been deeply hurt, we sometimes resist offering forgiveness, thinking that a pardon excuses the wrongdoer and downplays the severity of the wrong done to us. but thatâ€™s not what forgiveness isâ€”itâ€™s letting go of both the offense and our right to demand payment, with the acknowledgment that vengeance is godâ€™s responsibility, not ours (rom. 12:17-21). stubbornly refusing to forgive may seem like a way to get even, but itâ€™s actually a poison that harms us. it hampers our ability to enjoy life and, like any sin, erodes our fellowship with the lord. unforgiveness could even affect our health, resulting in physical illness, anxiety, or depression.

but roots of bitterness donâ€™t stop with us; they reach into our relationships, causing trouble and defiling others (heb. 12:15). an unforgiving spirit hinders our ability to love, poisoning the atmosphere in homes and workplaces.

isnâ€™t it time to deal with that root of bitterness? lay down your grievances and refuse to rehearse your hurts. then fill your mind with positive things insteadâ€”namely, truths about the lord.

a root of bitterness

hebrews 12:12-15

if youâ€™ve ever tried to get rid of weeds in your lawn or garden, you know what a big problem they can be. you pull them out, and everything looks really good for a while, but before long, the unwanted growth returns because the roots are still there.
an unforgiving spirit is like a root branching out in all directions, affecting every area of our life. lopping off the leaves by repressing the pain and resentment isnâ€™t a long-term solution, because like a weed, bitterness can continue to grow and reproduce as long as roots are in place.

when weâ€™ve been deeply hurt, we sometimes resist offering forgiveness, thinking that a pardon excuses the wrongdoer and downplays the severity of the wrong done to us. but thatâ€™s not what forgiveness isâ€”itâ€™s letting go of both the offense and our right to demand payment, with the acknowledgment that vengeance is godâ€™s responsibility, not ours (rom. 12:17-21). stubbornly refusing to forgive may seem like a way to get even, but itâ€™s actually a poison that harms us. it hampers our ability to enjoy life and, like any sin, erodes our fellowship with the lord. unforgiveness could even affect our health, resulting in physical illness, anxiety, or depression.

but roots of bitterness donâ€™t stop with us; they reach into our relationships, causing trouble and defiling others (heb. 12:15). an unforgiving spirit hinders our ability to love, poisoning the atmosphere in homes and workplaces.

isnâ€™t it time to deal with that root of bitterness? lay down your grievances and refuse to rehearse your hurts. then fill your mind with positive things insteadâ€”namely, truths about the lord.
dr. charles stanley

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin

cnn

text:
ğŸ‘ new episode sponsored by @foundcoffeela: @aapiwomenlead: #imready ğŸ‘ (link in bio)
.
after coming back from a retreat for asian american women, i have fostered a deeper appreciation for physical spaces dedicated solely for asian women. thatâ€™s why  dr. connie wun (@seewun) is here today to share about her upcoming launch of #imready, being held from november 3rd-4th, 2018. she will be sharing how she founded her own organization for aapi women as the director of aapi women lead, â€œan intergenerational organization that strengthens the social and political power of aapi communities through the leadership of aapi women-identified, women and girls in solidarity with other communities of color.â€
.
â€œthe #imready movement aims to strengthen the progressive political and social platforms of asian and pacific islander communities in the us through the leadership of self-identified aapi women and girls.  our goal is to challenge and help end the intersections of violence against and within our communities. we do this work in solidarity with other communities of color.
.
the #imready movement raises visibility around self-identified aapi women and our experiences with #metoo, racial discrimination, war, immigration, and more. it also celebrates the leadership and power of aapi women in education, business, technology, and politics. at the conferences, we bring together aapi women leaders and our supporters to learn from one another, tell our stories, and to highlight our diverse leadership stories.
.
we invite you to join us to better understand the complex asian and pacific islander diasporas, histories, and experiences. we invite you to come honor the stories and leadership of our communities.
.
we are bringing together some of the most brilliant people to explore what it means to be a self-identified aapi woman in the united states. we know you are one of them.â€
.
connie wun, ph.d., is co-founder of aapi women lead, a non-profit organization that helps to support the progressive social and political platforms of asian and pacific islander communities in the u.s through the leadership of self-identified women and girls.
.

in life, your self-belief will be under constant assault from the outside. - true growth, and the journey to unconditional self-acceptance, begins on the inside, though.
.
@themindshiftacademy iâ€™ve walked through the fire. iâ€™ve been emotionally burned, scarred and rebuilt from within. and now... i know my truth, i live my truth and i project my truth.
â€”> the result? people are magnetically drawn to my inner strength... like a moth to the flame.
.
realizing my true worth was like being born again. i felt transformed. recreated. alive.

text:
voice 
majlis' project for the month is based on the #metoo campaigning that has shaken the country awake. 
it is very evident that harassment and assault of all kinds have been prevalent all around us for ages, but why didn't we know? what stopped the victims from speaking up? what stopped them from sharing their stories? why didn't we hear their voice? 
voice is a series of posts on the several very real reasons why people didn't speak up as told to us by harassment survivors themselves. 
#voice #useyourvoice #useyourwords #voicemajlis
#metoo #metooindia
art by @xaraa_aa

text:
so proud to be a #xoogler today. respect to the 20000+ #googlers who believed the stories of survivors instead of getting distracted by all the noise and planned the #googlewalkout. in my 4 years tenure in google and even post leaving google, i heard and witnessed such terrible incidents first hand where power hungry #googler and #xoogler predators just believed, they could get away with any kind of #harassment just because they were #google alums and that women had to "try it" cuz who cares about #consent. 
yes that's literally what an ex-google management level employee thought he could get away with even after leaving #google. the #groping, #pinching and absolute crassy behaviour happened right in front of my eyes to someone i care a lot for and it made me feel helpless and absolutely gutted that #she still had to be graceful about it cuz she didn't want it to hurt my career. kudos to her for being an absolute warrior and a true friend who chose to put my interests before her own safety. i finally did find my voice and threw him out of the room, but he still did not relent, throwing in the nonchalant "try it" #shamelessly before finally leaving. this #walkout needs to be a constant reminder to any past, present and future predators from #google. the #purge has begun and #googlers are clearly showing how they want to be remembered for inspiring employees around the world to stand up to sexual harassment. time is up! #google #googlers #timeisup #metoo #googlewalkout #inspirational #woke #inspired #united #xoogler #googler #consent #timesup #friendship #notokgoogle #dontbeevil

text:
thank you to everyone who came to my book launch in cookham last night at the media hub. it was one of the most poignant moments of my life and career.

i was blown away by the support i had from my close friends and family to the people i didnâ€™t know, it was a really great friendly evening with such a warm energy emulating from the room. i couldnâ€™t have asked for a better first night out on this.

speaking about my journey is never easy but it is the right thing for me to now do. i want my voice to give hope to others and give back opportunities for you to succeed.

donâ€™t hold back is full of interactive activities and advice to improve your life, make you think differently, find new challenges and face your fears. if youâ€™d like a signed copy iâ€™ll be in henley next friday.

for more information on my book, signings or opportunities please email emmajanepa@gmail.com and speak with julie.

thank you to sarah parfitt for co-ordinating such a wonderful evening, my publisher naz ahsun, vision maker press for believing in me and to my production team, julie green, vivienne m clark, ross arrowsmith for guiding me with passion and talent!

i couldnâ€™t be here without the support i get, so thank you to all from the bottom of my heart for being with me last night.

text:
~
yes yes, i'm back with more.
more poems on rape.
more words to pour,
oh and although i save none, 
i'm doing better than you've done.

infant? yes.
schoolgirl? yes.
employee? yes.
granny? hell yes.

i've heard it all.
just wanted to know?
it just doesn't matter how old they grow?
india is just not safe though.

i sing my national anthem with pride.
but if you just keep quiet as many die.
and those who survive can never be a bride,
as the world gives them no place to hide.

hey guys, behave.
hey girls, be safe.
~suhas achanta

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
this #femalefounderfriday we're highlighting brazilian native daniela perdomo co-founded gotenna in 2012 with her brother, jorge, in brooklyn just after hurricane sandy tore through the eastern seaboard and knocked out power and cell service for thousands of people.

taking out nearly a quarter of all cell towers, the storm rendered communication virtually impossible at a very crucial time. â€œgiven we have supercomputers (phones) on us all the time, we decided that wasnâ€™t acceptable,â€ perdomo, 32, recalled. â€œthere needed to be a resilient phone-to-phone network that was people-powered, not dependent on large-scale solutions that fail us when we need them most.â€ gotenna creates decentralized connectivity through what it describes as the worldâ€™s first mobile, long-range mesh networks via peer-to-peer communications devices. it has two devices on the market, gotenna mesh and gotenna pro, both of which create independent mesh networks that let users send texts and share gps locations without cell service or wifi. the devices pair to regular phones as the interface.

the startup has raised a total of $16.8 million from investors such as union square ventures, walden venture capital, mentortech ventures, bloomberg beta, bbg ventures, and collaborative fund.

gotenna mesh is the companyâ€™s consumer device and began shipping mid-summer 2017. it has been adopted by more than 100,000 people and available in 42 countries, according to perdomo. each node acts as a relay for other devices, extending the range for everyone in the network.

like zatarain, perdomo â€“ who grew up in sao paulo and moved to the u.s. when she was 18 â€“ believes the latinx population is harder to quantify or identify because it comes â€œin literally every color.â€ â€œeven our names donâ€™t always clarify things,â€ she said. â€œlatin america is a melting pot.â€ when it comes to being a minority co-founder, perdomo believes she probably gets discriminated against more due to her gender than her ethnic origin.

we love highlighting and celebrating our female founders who shatter the glass ceiling. 
#steam #stem  #tech #innovation #weareinnovators #timesup #metoo #weareinnovators #wwt2018 #wonderwomentech

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
u.s. president donald trump's former aide steve bannon sought to use personal information collected online to promote "a culture war," a whistleblower christopher wiley on now-defunct political data firm cambridge analytica told u.s. senators on wednesday.

bannon, a former cambridge analytica vice president, "saw cultural warfare as a means to create enduring change in american politics," testified christopher wylie, who says information about tens of millions of facebook (fb.o) users ended up in cambridge analytica's hands.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
persephoneâ€™s rising molecular dancer

it's an odd experience creating a work i know will be around long after my grandchildren have come and gone... they are messages in bottles to the future cast towards a better more compassionate and inspired possibility, ... and combined with being present to the pressures of my current experience being feels all at once  gratifying and terrifying, perplexing and egotistical, defeated and hopeful (not all at once, mind you, but as waves of a great ocean upon the shores of my existence). corey allen reminded me recently that happiness is the smoke that rises from what's being done and what i am doing... it is not a goal or tangible object, only the wisps of the burning of being and the embers of doing. which sounds and feels like the buddhist's evocative description of forgiveness, the fragrance of the flower after it has been plucked or crushed.

#metoo #metoomovement #women #womenempowerment #femalesculpture

text:
lord, we praise you for being faithful to us. lord we know that your name is above every name... even depression. we know that each person that is dealing with depression deals with it in a different way. we pray that you meet them at the point of their need. lord, you have the power to lift this depression off of the one suffering right now.  give them hope lord like only you can. help them to rely completely on your strength when they have none. regulate the chemicals in the brain that causes the sickness. lord, somebody needs you right now. they are desperately seeking complete and total healing. someone wants to smile, but can't. give them a reason to smile again. lord, please remove the hurt and the pain forever. mend their broken hearts. we know that there isn't one universal event that causes the onset of depression, so help us to show compassion and love to those who we know are dealing with this illness. lord, although we may not know all the signs of depression, nor can we always tell when someone is depressed, guide our feet to someone who may be dealing with it. give us a kind word to share that will help them go on. put someone in their path that will whisper a prayer for them, someone that will give them that hug that they need, someone that will sing a song that will tell touch their heart, or just a smile that will help them feel like they can make it. lord, we know that you are sovereign and you do all things well.  we thank you in advance for hearing our prayer and meeting our needs in the mighty name of jesus we pray. amen.
.
.

text:
it's not your fault, no matter what they say. it's not a survivor's fault and it's okay to take your time healing the wounds. it's okay to still have wounds that you could not get over. you and only you are the one who can decide what you should feel about your harassment, what step you wish to take and when you wish to speak up.

many brave women are speaking up about the abuse of their personal space and their consent and we admire their courage. it takes immense strength to speak up about sexual harassment and fuzia supports each survivor. 
if you wish to share your own story with the world, you can message us and we will publish it anonymously (or publicly if you wish to). we stand in solidarity with you, not and always.

___

text:
growing up i never really worried about any major social issues. i always felt safe, didn't see any injustices towards me for the fact of being a woman. but now that i've traveled so much, met so many people, and educated myself by reading i understand how this is not the case for every woman. not even all women in my own country. (this is just one more reason why i think euskadi is such a special place but i leave that for another post). the fact is that we are being assassinated, raped, abused and being thought of as less for our gender, and still have it denied in our faces. we see how judges question us instead of our agressors, because our skirt was too short or because we were out at night by ourselves. and my concern here is why are men not standing up against this with us? why are some women also denying these facts?
my answer is because of toxic masculinities. and because we, women of the world, are taught to compete against each other and love and take care of the men while they are allowed to have an accepting environment among themselves.
#metoo #niunamenos

text:
tuesday is the most consequential election in my lifetime so far. i'm going to be out of the country for the midterms so i made sure to get my mail-in ballot and sent it in today.
. . . . 
i believe the heart + soul of our country is at stake. we need to... stand up for racial + social justice. stand up for saving our planet. stand up for protecting our reproductive rights. stand up for caring for children being ripped apart from their families. stand up for human decency, kindness, compassion and empathy. stand up everyone's right to vote. . . . . 
which side of history do you want to be on? get to the polls on tuesday and do your civic duty. . . . . 
art via @ericcomstock . . . .

the egg industry is one of the most inherently cruel of those in today's world of animal exploitation.
.
layer hens are kept in decrepit conditions, regardless of whether the carton states free range or organic! an inability to fluff and groom their feathers, extend their wings, scratch and graze and socialise drive the poor animals insane.
.
layer hens are selectively bred, genetically modified and manipulated into laying an unnatural amount of eggs compared to what they would naturally.
.
male chicks cannot lay eggs and are therefore considered a waste product. they are stuffed into plastic bags where they are left to suffocate or they are dropped into a macerator alive and turned into a pink pulp.
.
not to mention they are full of cholesterol and carcinogens!
. 
don't directly contribute to the murder and severe mistreatment of these poor, innocent beings. boycott eggs. be vegan. make the world a better place to live for all species that share the planet with us!

repost from @robynwilkerson - over decades of ministry iâ€™ve counseled women who have dealt with various forms of sexual harassment. with the recent #metoo movement, the topic has become big news, and it is starting to get the attention it deserves.

letâ€™s lay all of the cards out on the table. sexual harassment is one of those insidious evils that surround us. it lurks in the background and we donâ€™t really pay much attention to it until it directly affects us in some way.

as women, we are often told we need to â€œmove pastâ€ any â€œuncomfortableâ€ situations weâ€™ve experienced. as in the situation made us uncomfortable, but thatâ€™s the extent of it, giving the impression the woman is overreacting. all too often, sexual harassment is swept under the rug, or dealt with quietly so the situation just goes away.

i focus on two areas of this important topic in my newest blog post. first, i look a little closer at sexual harassment: what it is, who it affects, and what kind of damage it causes. then i look at the steps someone who is sexually harassed can take to find healing and how we can help.

.
.
.
trumpâ€™s former lawyer says the ex-reality tv star frequently made offensive and racist comments in private â€” even telling him during the 2016 campaign he believed â€œblack people are too stupid to vote for me.â€ michael cohen told vanity fair on friday that he often heard trump make such comments behind closed doors. 
cohen recounted a discussion he had with the then-presidential candidate at trump tower in 2016 in which the one-time trump confidante noted that the crowd at a rally earlier in the day was largely caucasian.
â€œi told trump that the rally looked vanilla on television. trump responded, â€˜thatâ€™s because black people are too stupid to vote for me,â€™â€ cohen told the magazine.

years earlier, shortly after the death of nelson mandela, cohen claims that trump asked him to, â€œname one country run by a black person thatâ€™s not a s---hole,â€ adding, â€œname one city.â€
â€œiâ€™m not surprised at all,â€ a source with ties to the white house told the daily news. â€œso many people have come forward with similar stories.â€ cohen also recalled a trip in the 2000s in which he and trump were riding in a car riding through a run-down neighborhood in chicago on the way to a business meeting. trump took note of his surroundings and said something to the effect of â€œonly the blacks could live like this.â€ another racist comment came from trump when the pair were discussing past seasons of â€œthe apprentice.â€ the two were talking about the showâ€™s first season, which ended with two contestants, bill rancic and kwame jackson, in a head-to-head.
â€œtrump was explaining his back-and-forth about not picking jackson,â€ an african-american investment manager who had graduated from harvard business school, cohen said. â€œhe said, â€˜thereâ€™s no way i can let this black f-g win.â€™â€ stay focused! donâ€™t get discouraged, get mad, fight harder & smarter than republicans, get even! go vote and take 5 people with you. #votolatino #rockthevote #democrats #midterms #bluewave  #blacklivesmatter #blackgirlsrock #voterregistration #voting  #votingday #metoo #women #trump #racism  #votersuppression #vote #voteblue

text:
this holiday season, remember, everyone's abuser has not moved on and is not just accepting things as they are. things are tough on them as well, they may have a family that they may feel has been broken up. they will act out because that is their nature. create a safety word if you feel endangered or plain ole sad. allow a few people around you to know that word or phrase so they can spring into action. create a plan for when the word is said. it is as simple as saying, "wow, this sweater is itchy" or "i do not like pumpkin pie". the plan is to keep you and everyone around safe. create it based on something that you don't like or something simple, but create it so you can get support you need. don't suffer in silence this year.

text: welp. were not friends.....if ur not voting on november 6th.............. if you think your vote does not matter or that these issues do not pertain to you or that im being dramatic you are just wrong. this election directly effects everyone and everyone should be concerned. at least two years of unrestricted trump bills!!! unrestricted oppression of all marginalized groups that will pass through congress!!! you really dont care that he is killing millions of people and our planet??? if you cannot see that our present day government is a result of all events that happened since slavery and civil rights (only like 60 years ago) and that no joke the same people have been in office for 50+ years because there are no term limits for senate, hr and supreme court. yes. really. research jamie whitten, john dingell, robert byrd and sooo many more. they stayed in office for 50+ years and a lot of them voted no on the civil rights act and voting rights act that gave black people the right to vote and had a say in our laws well into the 2000â€™s!!!!! yes some democrats are corrupt and greedy. but so is our whole government that was built off of racism and suppression where all those old white people (~80% white) let me repeat 80 percent white in congress have been there for decades deciding who can and cant have rights and where all the money goes. these corrupt old rich white people with old bigoted views want you not to vote so they can keep their long-standing power. they dont teach systems of oppression in school for a reason! our government decides what is taught and ignorance=complacency! everything they are doing rn is destructive. it is a slow process yes, but not contributing is basically a vote for the other side. a vote for complacency and white supremacy. isnt the logic pretty clear here??? if you have read this far thank you and i hope you can think about your position and amount of privilege you have or dont have in our world and recognize that this is an opportunity to help your family/ your own standing towards equality and the equality of others who you may have innately benefited off of because of history. so use the only power you are given and vote blue.

text:

i couldn't help but think about his every day life.

some d-bag bought him lunch and i used that opportunity to hijack the photo opp he paid for.

text:
the great commandment. the great commission.

the 2018 gc2 summit on #metoo/#churchtoo is a one-day event which will challenge and inspire pastors, leaders, and lay christians to address the very real tragedy in our churches and to begin the healing process of being who god designed all of us to be. we will bring together top leaders today to address what the bible says about this tragedy, the destruction of silence, how to protect those who are vulnerable and victimized, the role of accountability in leadership, and much more.

#tbt ...to one of the last trail races i competed in - jan 2017. 
was asked just yesterday - "do you miss trail running?" ...ugh. it's so hard to convey my sentiments...this sport became a lifestyle to me. yes, the endorphins and racing are addicting but the comaraderie was phenomenal! 
don't think i'll be back anytime soon but to those who can, embrace your moments and friendships.

the ever-so-amazing bartender â€“ pippa guy â€“ whoâ€™s added a fierce energy, grace and softness to the award-winning american bar at the savoy hotel.
.
weâ€™re just getting to know pippa â€“ weâ€™ve met a couple of times. pippa is just heading into her 6th year as a bartender, and she firmly believes that â€œyou get out what you put in â€“ there are so many people that work incredibly hard, but thereâ€™s not enough support and appreciation towards everyoneâ€™s dedication.â€ over the next three years, pippa hopes to see the industry become even more conscious of our impact on the environment. sheâ€™s hoping that each of us will take more of a leading role in this cause â€“ how do we look after â€œwasteâ€, what is â€œwasteâ€ and how do we manage the world around us? .
.
when it comes to the drinks industry, and when it comes to making a difference, pippaâ€™s advice is simple â€œstop doubting yourselfâ€. pippaâ€™s journey at the savoy is ear marked by a figure she would love to chat with â€“ ada coleman â€“ the first and only female head bartender at the american bar. â€œfrom the records we have, ada seems to be a pretty fiery character, but also took quite a lot of unpleasant treatment in her position. iâ€™d love to buy her a martini and listen to her stories. sheâ€™s ultra-inspiring.â€ .
beyond the savoy, pippa desperately wants to spend some time in california â€“ after all, her mum was born there, and craves some family and beach time! if pippa wasnâ€™t bartending, sheâ€™d most likely something to do within the science, sport or travel industries; â€œiâ€™ve always thought iâ€™d really enjoy marine biology, the problem is, iâ€™d be awful at sitting behind a desk for long periods of time â€“ how can people get anything done sitting in one spot for so long?!â€ the perfect moment for a cocktail? â€œiâ€™m a complete sun worshiper, so after a long day in the sun, just towards sunset, somewhere outside with a good view, iâ€™m drinking a gin & tonic.â€ .
.
pippaâ€™s one line that describes her, â€œthere is freedom waiting for you, on the breezes of the sky, and you ask â€˜what if i fall?â€™ oh but my darling, what if you fly?â€ wise words from erin hanson.

i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

.

text:
the other day, i asked my boyfriend, â€œwhatâ€™s my worst quality?â€ iâ€™ve been working on bettering myself lately, and i knew heâ€™d give me an honest answer. i assumed heâ€™d say that i was impatient or that i would talk over him too much. his answered surprised me. he said, â€œyou doubt yourself too much.â€ i knew he was right, but i never thought it was my worst quality. he reminded me even though i am doing well at my new job and how i successfully run her every day, i still donâ€™t believe in myself. i doubt that what iâ€™m doing with her is impactful for others. i doubt that my efforts for her are good enough. i doubt my abilities and worry that iâ€™m not doing well enough at work. i even doubt my relationships with friends and family. and truth be told, if i had a friend who was like me, i would probably think sheâ€™s pretty badass. but because itâ€™s me, i always compare myself to others and only see my flaws. .
why is this? often, survivors who have been manipulated, controlled, or gaslighted, tend to lose trust in themselves. the pressure to be perfect for our abusers (which is self-imposed after the abuse) is a lingering effect of trauma. .

text:
an essential read. clarissa pinkola estÃ©s, the women who run with the wolves. 'while much psychology emphasises the familial causes of angst in humans, the cultural component carries as much weight, for culture is the family if the family. if the family of the family has various sicknesses, then all families within that culture will have to struggle with the same malaises. in my heritage, there is a saying, 'cultura cura', culture cures. if the culture is a healer, the families learn how to heal; they will struggle less, be more reparative, far less wounding, far more graceful and loving. in a culture where the predator rules, all new life needing to be born, all old life needing to be gone, is unable to move and the soul-lives of its citizenry are paralysed with both fear and spiritual famine.' this quote actually jumped out at the time of dr christine blasey ford's courageous testimony. now we're thinking about all those who are doing the work of making culture that cures. people like @alokvmenon and @travisalabanza and @leopardprintelephant who share the experience of being gender non-conforming and non-binary, giving inspiration and hope and beauty to so many; organisations like @rapecrisisscotland who create a save haven for survivors of abuse; and further afield, cultural leaders like @jadapinkettsmith @busyphilipps and @lavernecox who inspire us with their womanhood every damn day. 
#thewomenwhorunwithwolves #feminist #intersectionalfeminism #transisbeautiful #translivesmatter #believewomen #metoo #timesup #representationmatters

'while much psychology emphasises the familial causes of angst in humans, the cultural component carries as much weight, for culture is the family if the family. if the family of the family has various sicknesses, then all families within that culture will have to struggle with the same malaises. in my heritage, there is a saying, 'cultura cura', culture cures. if the culture is a healer, the families learn how to heal; they will struggle less, be more reparative, far less wounding, far more graceful and loving. in a culture where the predator rules, all new life needing to be born, all old life needing to be gone, is unable to move and the soul-lives of its citizenry are paralysed with both fear and spiritual famine.' this quote actually jumped out at the time of dr christine blasey ford's courageous testimony. now we're thinking about all those who are doing the work of making culture that cures. people like @alokvmenon and @travisalabanza and @leopardprintelephant who share the experience of being gender non-conforming and non-binary, giving inspiration and hope and beauty to so many; organisations like @rapecrisisscotland who create a save haven for survivors of abuse; and further afield, cultural leaders like @jadapinkettsmith @busyphilipps and @lavernecox who inspire us with their womanhood every damn day. 
#thewomenwhorunwithwolves #feminist #intersectionalfeminism #transisbeautiful #translivesmatter #believewomen #metoo #timesup #representationmatters

even though she was allowed to socialize with cameronâ€™s wife, janice and even visit her mother, she still continued to live in the box and did not attempt to escape or even reach out for help.

eventually, she was freed by janice, who asked stan to not disclose her abuse as janice was attempting to reform cameron. stan remained silent until janice finally decided to turn cameron over to the police. this is a very famous example of the infamous condition called stockholm syndrome.
stockholm syndrome is a condition where a captive or victim of abuse, begins to psychologically or even emphatically bond with his/her captor or abuser.

stockholm syndrome is more involved in the sustenance of abusive relationships than most people know. leaving any relationship (abusive or not) is never easy; making up your mind to leave someone who youâ€™ve shared so much with in so long a time is not an easy fit. but then, there are extreme cases where everyone else sees the life threatening danger, so does the victim, but he/she decides to keep going back after every beat down and maltreatment.
studies show that abuse (whether emotional or physical), blended with moments of kindness can bond some victims to their abusers even more than consistent good treatment can. in most abusive relationships, especially emotionally abusive ones, the victim has chances to leave and escape but they do not. 
it might also interest you to know that â€˜belleâ€™ from â€˜beauty and the beastâ€™ is considered by many to be a victim of stockholm syndrome.

text:
read the caption

it's been almost a month since the #metoo storm took a full swing all over the social media and there hasn't been any justice given to these victims. have they?? i don't think so. the victims have been tortured in all possible ways and they have been physically and emotionally weak, that they have shut themselves down from everyone and pushed to the verge of ending their lives. indeed, some have ended their lives. and the survivors are living their lives like a living dead. i'm not exaggerating anything here. no matter how much support we give them, how much we listen to them, the horrific experiences that they had gone through can never be forgotten or understood by us. and if they forget, the wound pricks every time, they read about yet another incident. it is like the worst nightmare coming to reality. i appreciate everyone of us supporting, listening and standing by the sides of these victims and helping them to raise their voice against their perpetrators. it takes immense courage for these women to open up after everything that they have been through and there comes the group of men and to my surprise women slut shaming them. what does it take for you people to empathize for a fellow human? if you are not going to be of any help, then don't just say anything. they have already been tortured in and out and these group ask insensitive questions and claims like, "why didn't you say then?; what took you so long? ; what is your motive? ; oh, she is just seeking attention; what is your caste?" wait. what? yeah, you read it right. caste. like it matters so much to raise one's voice for justice. these questions sounds like, "this is what happens in this country, that's nothing new. they are doing what have to do and let's see what you can do about it" with a huge evil grin on the face. and i'm so ashamed to say but this is what is happening in this country. #metoo storm hit every social media platforms and there have been endless cases against several personalities from different walks of life. alright, now these slut shaming group would say, "these victims are hiding behind the smart screens, they are alleging anonymously for whatsoever reasons"
name: Sonia Sasidharan

the past few days i found myself getting more and more upset at my friend because she wasn't communicating with me. i was angry because she wasn't being honest with me, and i almost lashed out at her.
â€¢
honestly, i was hurt. but i remembered statements about what i can control. i can't control what she does or what she shares with me, but i can control how i respond to her and how i handle my frustrations.
â€¢
the hardest lesson i've learned is to let go. the number of things i can control is incredibly small when compared to things  out of my control. this weekend, i challenge everyone to recognize one thing you can't control, and let go. - diane

text:
just a reminder that you have until december 31st to submit your stories for my #metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.
get your stories in! be heard! help others know that they are not alone.
.
my latest project is called â€œ#metoo: a collection of true story crimes against women.â€
i am still collecting stories. submissions will be accepted until december 31, 2018.
if you have a story that you would like to include email me at mchillstromauthor@yahoo.com.
all stories will be listed as anonymous submissions.
the types of stories i am looking for include personal experiences of:
-sexual harassment -rape/assault -sexual, emotional, or physical abuse
-stalking
-gender discrimination
-i will accept other topics if they fit in with the theme as well.
through writing my own stories i have found peace and strength.
i hope others will find this as well along with the knowledge that they are not alone.
proceeds from the sales of this collection will be donated to help sexual assault survivors.
.
.

link in bio for complete video. freddie mercury is one of my favorite singers. he is a man who sang with the essence of his true creativity, passion and sensuality. he quotes, â€œi won't be a rock star. i will be a legend,â€ and so he is!  today, #bohemianrhapsodymovie movie is being released, and in honor of him, i decided to arrange an acoustic mash-up version of my favorite queen/bowie song, â€œunder pressureâ€ and â€œi want to break free.â€ as a child, i didnâ€™t really understand itâ€™s meaningâ€“i just felt something. all these years later, the message is just as powerful and important - if not even more so today to me, itâ€™s about the struggle we all face to transcend the pressure of a dualistic world obsessed with perfection and to find the love within, that heals us all. itâ€™s about being true to who we are and not letting the weight of â€œthe worldâ€ destroy us. it can be about so many things to so many people. i just hope the message touches your heart in some way, as it did mine. please share with those who might need a lift.

text: happy 1 year sober to me :p i honestly can't believe it's been a year already. some may not think it's a big deal but it is to me. after smoking pot everyday for almost 6 years i'm proud that i don't even think about it or want it anymore. 6 years ago i was dealing with the mental after effects of sexual assault and used alcohol and pot to try to forget. i've come a long way since then and am so glad that i've dealt with all of those negative feelings and understand that it wasn't my fault. if you are struggling, there's always a way out. just gotta start talking about it and ask for help. #sober #1yearsober #metoo #happy #youcandoittoo #noshame #endthestigma

one thing we will be working on and emphasizing during the retreat is the power of release. feeling what you feel, allowing yourself to feel it, and giving yourself permission to let it flow through you.
â€¢
we will go into detail about how release or discharge of the nervous system is vital to resetting. to being. we are human beings with the incredible capability to f e e l. it isnâ€™t wrong or right. it isnâ€™t good or bad. it just is.
â€¢

text:

the criticism of the way the media depicts gender wasnâ€™t just something i was reading about, it was something i was inadvertently contributing to. by encouraging the women to behave in a more stereotypical feminine manner, i was fostering established stereotypes in representation. in times without significant forethought, it can be easy to default to some preconceived notions or behaviors.  just as i did. read the original article here: https://goodmenproject.com/social-justice-2/my-accidental-gender-stereotyping-cmtt/

text:
the impact of trauma can be intense and long lasting. healing from trauma may mean intensive and long-term treatment, as the impact trauma has on memory, the body, and the nervous system, can be profoundâ €
ğŸ’œâ €
trauma memories have a big impact on survivorsâ€™ explicit and implicit memory. trauma can shut down parts of memory, can cause survivors to be triggered without explanation, and can change patterns in procedural memoryâ €
ğŸ’œâ €
all of these memory related shifts can lead to increased dissociation, and unwanted somatic experiences that may be unexplained. the body may feel pain or numbness as a response to a trauma trigger, and since the survivorâ€™s brain is off line (during dissociation) they may lack the context for what is happening. here, the mind, body, and nervous system are trapped in the trauma memory â €
ğŸ’œâ €
in these moments, it often feels like your body is betraying you, and you may feel increased distress which could make way for feelings of guilt or shameâ €
ğŸ’œâ €
this process may be circular, and it may take trauma-informed therapy (and other trauma-informed treatments) to get the mind, body, and nervous system, all on the same page. donâ€™t give up on your healing, with increased awareness and self-acceptance, you will learn to cope with your trauma in ways that are in service of your healing ğŸ’œâ €

text:
im not one to get political, partly cause thereâ€™s a lot i do not understand when it comes to politics and governmentâ€¦ but during this current administration, i am constantly (almost daily) shocked and saddened by the things being said and done by our so-called leader. but, we always have to try and find a positive in everything, and i always try make to every experience or event a â€˜lesson learnedâ€™ â€¦. in september, when the kavanaugh hearings were going on, i tried in my best way, to explain to my girls what was going onâ€¦ before, during and afterâ€¦the trials and especially when dr #christineblaseyford was on the standâ€¦. and it was a good time to explain boundaries , consent and respect â€¦ when the decision was made to appoint kavanaugh, i was in disbelief, and saddened to say the leastâ€¦ but again, learning experience, and i was very glad that the lines of communication were opened and my girls and i were able to touch on the subject. it also opened up the conversation for me to tell them, things like this should not happen, and women need to be represented in all areas, but especially government. the lawmakers and law enforcers should represent the people, all people, not just a certain gender or color. sometimes i wonder and think if they â€˜get itâ€™â€¦. or if it just sounds like â€˜blahblahblahâ€™ when i talkâ€¦ lol

well, this week was spirit week at gracieâ€™s school @kippsol â€¦ and today was â€˜support your causeâ€™ dayâ€¦ assignment: â€˜advocate for yourself and support what you stand for and believeâ€¦â€™â€¦ so gracie said â€˜how about dr ford â€¦â€™ so i proudly  present to you, my love, my flaquita, my tutuâ€¦. as dr. christine blasey ford (sorry we didnâ€™t get a wigâ€¦ lol)â€¦ but ayyyy my gracie makes me so proud!! i think
she gets it!! cause dr. ford is a true hero!! and despite the trauma she suffered, her courage to come forward and speak the #truth, none of it was in vain.... thereâ€™s a whole new generation of young girls watching... learning... and i hope, one day will #takeaction ... #changetheworld #advocate #believewomen #webelieve #timesup #metoo #speakup #thefutureisfemale  @kippsol @kippschools #wecandoit #sisepuede #ibelievechristineblaseyford #@kipplapublicschools @mazilove27

text:
over decades of ministry iâ€™ve counseled women who have dealt with various forms of sexual harassment. with the recent #metoo movement, the topic has become big news, and it is starting to get the attention it deserves.

letâ€™s lay all of the cards out on the table. sexual harassment is one of those insidious evils that surround us. it lurks in the background and we donâ€™t really pay much attention to it until it directly affects us in some way.

as women, we are often told we need to â€œmove pastâ€ any â€œuncomfortableâ€ situations weâ€™ve experienced. as in the situation made us uncomfortable, but thatâ€™s the extent of it, giving the impression the woman is overreacting. all too often, sexual harassment is swept under the rug, or dealt with quietly so the situation just goes away.

i focus on two areas of this important topic in my newest blog post. first, i look a little closer at sexual harassment: what it is, who it affects, and what kind of damage it causes. then i look at the steps someone who is sexually harassed can take to find healing and how we can help.

one thing that really helped me put my past behind me is cbt (cognitive behavioural therapy). i learned that you can alter your experience by how you frame and think about what you've been through. you can actually change how you interpret and react to what you've been through. you can assess what happened and learn to see things differently. this in turn starts to impact how you handle your past and how you see things going forward. it eventually gets easier to accept, to learn from, to talk about and to grow from what happened. 
you can eventually go from victim to survivor

text:
there's so much (saddening) talk in my world about women - our restricted rights, our bodies as battlegrounds, the abuse and harassment we've experienced at work, the injustice of un-equal pay, the millions of us who have said #metoo in the past year... .
yet these conversation are critical if we're going to ensure the next generation doesn't have to go thru what we have. .
.
at the same time, nothing will change unless men change too. we cant do it alone. that's why this post is about the incredible men in my life, and how they show up in the world. today, the work that my friend and mentor @saschaflavor has been doing with @_evryman_ was featured on national tv; it felt so good to see @jiivy front and center; what he said about redefining masculinity, intimacy and dismantling machismo is exactly what's needed to move forward .
.
earlier in the morning, my incredible friend @mjrothman sent me this image of him and our friend @cossmarte. good men who are giving, caring, compassionate entrepreneurs who seamlessly blend being successful with being open-hearted, honest and caring. coss came home from prison and built a program that provides jobs to the formerly incarcerated, and fitness to hundreds of people a day. mike doenst talk about it much, but he's literally traversed one end of the country to the other on a bike to raise money for people impacted by mass incarceration . .
.
i firmly believe men like the ones im lucky enough to love, are going to lead us forward. they do it by being committed to facing their own demons, going into their own pain, connecting to their bodies, and being open with each other. that in turn redefines how they show up at work, in relationships with their partners, and as friends . .
.
grateful to know you, grateful to love you and grateful for your collective leadership

text:
â€œthere is so much evidence. this is the era of the #metoo movement, but even before that there is so much evidence if we are willing to pay attention; that these traditional ways that women are vulnerable to being taken advantage of across a broad spectrum. we have known that many many women are vulnerable and have been victimized in some ways at some points in our lives â€“ i am one of those women. so itâ€™s a difficult time to be reminded of how prevalent it is and seeing the system responding in ways that are very apparently self-protective of the nominee, just to see that level of defensiveness and unwillingness perhaps to be open to what may be known is its own shocking revelation.â€ â€“ rhonda magee (@rvmagee)

this time on the bhnn guest podcast, @francescamaxime sits down for a conversation with professor rhonda v. magee about bringing mindfulness to systemic injustice.

rhonda v. magee is professor of law at the university of san francisco and is an internationally-recognized thought and practice leader on integrating mindfulness into higher education, law and social justice.

this podcast is brought to you by the generosity of @1440multiversity â€“ californiaâ€™s newest retreat destination which hosts a faculty of thought leaders in fields including mindfulness, neuroscience, relationships, the creative arts, and more.

text:
g witness october 
a review of the world in 57â€™ .
"it's been a year of shocking testimonies." - comments about the #metoo movement
.
october marks one year since the creation of #metoo. a once small and unspoken topic has grown exponentially and this has formed the foundation of the fempowerment movement, which will gain traction for years to come. it gave people a voice, a platform to stand on and has united millions of victims. rihanna took a stand against racism in the nfl by refusing to perform in the prestigious half time show. ms meaza ashanafi has made history by becoming the first female president of ethiopia, which is set to inspire a new generation of female political leaders.
.
kanye west and donald trump stole the show in the us by demonstrating to the world how two people with huge egos interact. as the public goes to the voting stations this month, 
the president should aim to be on his best behaviour as he seeks to garner the votes of the american people.
.
we are deeply saddened by the horrific killings at the pittsburgh synagogue, with a gunman taking the lives of 11 people. the sporting world was stunned as vichai srivaddhanaprabha tragically passed away in a freak helicopter accident. south africa lost a legend as hhp was found dead in his home. his music, charm and passion will be sorely missed.
.
back home, south africaâ€™s banking and government sectors were under the spotlight as the vbs scandal was brought to light. key players have had to answer uncomfortable questions about millions of missing rands. it will be interesting to see if newly elected financial minister mr tito mboweni will address this crisis.
.
as the end of the year is closing in, we need to prepare ourselves for more scandals, more ringside brawls and of course more people standing together for a cause.
.

text:
our #freestyle artist for the day is nneka uzoma gigi!
.
a contemporary visual artist, doctorial student and educator.
she is a multi talented artist, who specializes in paintings for print, body painting, haircrafts and sculpting.
.
.
today we feature an art sculpture piece, the very first of its kind called "amaka".
.
in her words:
a woman doesn't have to provide access to her body as proof she likes you.
.
.
my 1st sculpture ever, amaka, was created to shed light on the rape laws in nigeria while encouraging others to understand their own state laws regarding rape + sexual assault .
.
.
it was also a therapeutic exercise to discuss surviving my own rape from an emotional aspect all these years later...
.
.
to know more about gigi
instagram: @nnekagigi
website: www.nnekagigi.com
.
you can also read more about her on our website: http://www.thesparkng.com/contemporary-visual-art-nneka/ or see #linkinbio
.

text:
men are socialized to be strong, tough, unemotional, and brave. when little boys cry, they are told to â€œbuck up.â€ when they express emotional distress, they are told to â€œbe a man.â€ this societal repression of male emotionality results in the troubling construct known as toxic masculinity.
â€¢
#toxicmasculinity has many negative effects, including the perpetuation of the gender wage gap, sexual harassment, and intimate partner violence. another important ramification is the increased stigma around mental illness and seeking mental health services in those identifying as male.
â€¢
the @goodmenproject defines toxic masculinity as follows: toxic masculinity is a narrow and repressive description of manhood, designating manhood as defined by violence, sex, status and aggression. itâ€™s the cultural ideal of manliness, where strength is everything while emotions are a weakness; where sex and brutality are yardsticks by which men are measured, while supposedly â€œfeminineâ€ traitsâ€”which can range from emotional vulnerability to simply not being hypersexualâ€”are the means by which your status as â€œmanâ€ can be taken away.
â€¢
the idea that emotional vulnerability detracts from oneâ€™s status as a man is incredibly problematic for male mental health. in many cases, it results in an emotional style similar to a clinical syndrome known as alexithymia. those with alexithymia â€œhave difficulty describing their feelings, their cognitive style is concrete and reality-based, and they have impoverished emotional and fantasy livesâ€ (taylor et al., 1985).
â€¢
one study even found that men reporting greater gender role conflict endorsed greater levels of alexithymia and fear of intimacy (fischer & good, 1997). aside from the societal impacts of making men feel uncomfortable seeking mental health care, this has implications for those who do go to psychotherapy, which requires clients to connect with their thoughts and feelings in order to understand their psychiatric symptoms and interpersonal patterns.
â€¢
join us in supporting @themightysite in helping to reduce the stigma of mental illness and emotional expression in men by encouraging men to share their feelings with one another #itsokman
